<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910920-0038</DOCNO><DOCID>910920-0038.</DOCID><HL>   International:   Yeltsin Takes a Sick Day   As Parliament Convenes</HL><DATE>09/20/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A9</SO><RE>EASTERN EUROPE (EEU)EUROPE (EU)FAR EAST (FE)SOVIET UNION (UR)</RE><LP>   MOSCOW -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin missed theopening session of Parliament to spend the day at homeresting from a reportedly minor heart ailment that aidesdidn't exactly identify.   Mr. Yeltsin, 60 years old, was said to be suffering fromcardiac &quot;insufficiency,&quot; which some also described as apre-heart attack condition something like angina. A spokesmanfor his office said that the problem wasn't serious and thatMr. Yeltsin simply required some rest.</LP><TEXT>   Mr. Yeltsin, who was first reported ill on Wednesday,received visitors yesterday and was planning to fly today toNagorno-Karabakh in Azerbaijan to mediate between groupsfighting over territory, the spokesman said.   Because Mr. Yeltsin didn't require hospitalization and hisaides were playing down his problem, there was little visibleanxiety about the possibility that he might be too sick tocontinue his job. Mr. Yeltsin was hospitalized for chestpains in 1987.   Some members of the Russian Parliament speculated that Mr.Yeltsin might be feigning illness to avoid criticism fromthose who have grown unhappy with recent authoritariantendencies. His absence &quot;is seen by many deputies as anattempt to avoid open confrontation,&quot; deputy Vladimir Lisintold the Tass news agency. &quot;He would have had to answer somepretty unpleasant questions about his decrees.&quot;</TEXT></DOC>